AN  - 351790766
ID  - 18549961 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18549961]
T1  - Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome in the Adolescent-The Focus is New and Exciting
A1  - Sanfilippo J.S. 
Y1  - 2008//
N2  - We begin our story in utero, we must then monitor the patient during childhood as the incidence of obesity is increased, and then carefully reassess our patient at puberty. Addressing the physiologic/pathophysiology in a manner readily understood by both patient and parent facilitates having the teen truly involved in her own health care. Life-style change remains the one most important aspect in PCOS management whether we are dealing with a teenager or with an adult. As we learn more about the genetics, the role of insulin resistance, and its impact on ovarian function, we become better positioned to guide our patients in the right direction and maximize the benefits of evidence-based medicine in treating a common problem that each of us faces on a daily basis. © 2008 North American Society for Pediatric and Adolescent Gynecology.
