4127. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 352008734
T1  - Endocrine and metabolic changes in children receiving antiepileptic drugs
A1  - Verrotti A.
A1  - Di Marco G.
A1  - Chiarelli F. 
Y1  - 2007//
N2  - A large number of antiepileptic drugs are now available for the treatment of epileptic syndromes, but their use can be associated with various side-effects that may have a negative impact on the quality of life of epileptic children and adolescents. Among these side-effects, endocrine and metabolic dysfunctions are very frequent. Generally, they depend on mechanisms of action and dosage of antiepileptic drugs and duration of therapy. The underlying mechanisms often remain undefined and their nature is a matter of controversial scientific debate. The aim of this review is to analyze the main effects of antiepileptic drugs on metabolic and endocrine functions, in order to achieve a critical analysis of the recent studies on this topic and to improve the care of epileptic paediatric patients.
