AN  - 41341677
ID  - 16167871 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16167871]
T1  - Obesity, weight loss and bariatric surgery
A1  - O'Brien P.E.
A1  - Brown W.A.
A1  - Dixon J.B. 
Y1  - 2005//
N2  - * Obesity is shaping up to be the major health care problem and one of the most frequent causes of preventable death in Western countries in the 21st century. * Bariatric surgery is the only current treatment that has been shown to achieve major and durable weight loss. * Major weight loss in the severely obese leads to total or partial control of a wide range of common and serious diseases, such as diabetes, heart disease and hypertension. * Laparoscopic adjustable gastric banding is the most common type of obesity surgery performed in Australia. It is effective, relatively safe and minimally invasive. * The blocks to broader application of bariatric surgery should be identified and resolved.
