4263. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 43776690
ID  - 16737858 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16737858]
T1  - Metabolic Syndrome and Prediabetes
A1  - Babu A.
A1  - Fogelfeld L. 
Y1  - 2006//
N2  - The clustering of common conditions like hyperglycemia, hypertension, and dyslipidemia was first brought to attention by Gerald Reaven in the Banting lecture, 1998,1 and was called Syndrome X or the Insulin Resistance Syndrome. Since then, this constellation of metabolic risk factors has been called by various names, the latest being Metabolic Syndrome (MetSyn). This clinical entity reflects the major role that obesity, especially visceral obesity, plays as a determinant of insulin resistance that in turn leads to prothrombotic, inflammatory, and dyslipidemic state. This results in clinical consequences of hypertension, atherosclerosis, and finally, abnormal glucose tolerance and diabetes. Various organizations have since then published their own clinical criteria to identify the metabolic syndrome (Tables 1 and 2). Metabolic syndrome is a rising clinical challenge and is classified as a disease entity by the Center for Disease Control (CDC) and has an International Classification of Disease code of 277.7. It has received a great deal of attention in the past few years due to the fact that it has been linked to the development of both cardiovascular disease and type 2 diabetes. As more information emerges, other diseases are being linked to MetSyn, including nonalcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD), polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS), cancer, and obstructive sleep apnea. Recently, due to the various definitions of MetSyn, there has been controversy regarding both its components and its pathogenesis. The American Diabetes Association (ADA) and the European Association for the Study of Diabetes recently called for a closer examination of the definition of MetSyn.2 However, whichever definition is used, the incidence of MetSyn is high at present and continues to rise. This has been linked to the rising incidence of obesity in both the United States (US) and the rest of the world. MetSyn may be considered as a precondition of two major clinical entities that are in a constant rise: atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease and diabetes. Cardiovascular disease continues to be the major cause of death in both the US and the rest of the world. The incidence of diabetes at present in the US is estimated to be 20.8 million or 7% of the population3 In the year 2005 approximately 1.5 million new cases of diabetes were diagnosed in people aged 20 years or older. Direct medical and indirect expenditures attributable to diabetes in 2002 were estimated at $132 billion.4 Therefore, prevention of both diabetes and cardiovascular disease becomes very important. The identification of MetSyn provides a window of opportunity to recognize the risk for developing both diabetes and heart disease and start therapeutic measures to help prevent both conditions. In this monograph we will analyze the evidence associated with different views of the different organization and bring out the key points regarding the identification, diagnosis, and management of MetSyn that will be useful for the busy practicing primary care physicians. © 2006 Mosby, Inc. All rights reserved.
