4330. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 41658798
T1  - Increased intracranial pressure
A1  - Chaudhary A.K.
A1  - Tewari A. 
Y1  - 2005//
N2  - Intracranial pressure is the pressure of CSF with in the cranium. Increased intracranial pressure is a pathological state due to a number of diseases which add volume to the intracranial contents. Increased intracranial pressure results in cerebral insult by global hypoxic-ischemic injury which occurs due to reduced cerebral perfusion pressure and cerebral blood flow. It also causes mechanical distortion and compression of brain tissues via intracranial mass effect and ICP compartmentalization. Hence, the main aim of the treatment is to reduce the intracranial volume. In patients with acute rise in intracranial pressure, head elevation, hyperventilation and mannitol (1-2g/kg) rapidly lowers intracranial pressure. Presently, with the availability of sophisticated intracranial pressure monitoring systems, the management of increased intracranial pressure has improved dramatically. Sequential treatment should involve neuroimaging to exclude operable mass lesion, sedation to attain a quiet motionless state, blood pressure monitoring to keep CPP between 70 and 120, mannitol, hyperventilation to keep PCO2 between 30 to 35 mmHg and moderate hypothermia (32 to 33degreeC).
