4367. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 41272159
T1  - Abnormal uterine bleeding: A primary care primer
A1  - Miller J.
A1  - Holman J.R. 
Y1  - 2005//
N2  - A detailed menstrual cycle history is critical in women with abnormal uterine bleeding (AUB). if a patient has a history of intermenstrual bleeding, inquire about postcoital bleeding, which nay occur in the setting of cervicitis, polyps, or other cervical or vaginal lesions. Metrorrhagia and menometrorrhagia imply anovulation. Recommended laboratory tests include thyroid-stimulating hormone, lasting serum prolactin level, and cultures for Neisseria gonorrhoeae and Chlamydia. In women with menorrhagia who have evulatory cycles, ultrasonography is recommended to document uterine anatomy. Laboratory studies include measurement of hemoglobin level or hematocrit and a urinary human chorionic gonadotropin test. Postmenopausal bleeding warrants a complete assessment to rule out anatomic pathology and endometrial cancer. Options for management of AUB include oral contraceptives, NSAIDs, and hormone therapies.
