4380. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 41044410
ID  - 15976547 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15976547]
T1  - Managing disorders of ovulation: A model for evidence-based practice
A1  - Seif M.W. 
Y1  - 2005//
N2  - Ovulation disorders contribute significantly to female subfertility. Protocols of induction of ovulation are well established for first-line therapy and as an integral part of assisted reproduction procedures. There is an apparent degree of inconsistency when evidence of effectiveness of various therapeutic modalities is evaluated. This inconsistency prevails in the definition of primary and secondary outcomes. This is largely influenced by the settings in which various therapies are being investigated - whether alone or as part of assisted conception cycles - and by the significant heterogeneity which exists between clinical trials. Nevertheless, it remains disappointing that there is a paucity of data on the most relevant primary outcome, that is live birth, which poses significant limitations on the objective evaluation and on attempting comparison of the clinical effectiveness of different therapeutic modalities. Subsequently, the strength of evidence and of the recommendations resulting from critical appraisal and systematic reviews may be weakened, and their application to different settings and populations remains equivocal. Furthermore, cost and resource implications as well as adverse and secondary outcomes should be taken into consideration. Better understanding of the pathophysiology of disorders of ovulation has opened up new avenues for effective therapeutic approaches. However, valid and reliable evidence of effectiveness and data on long-term health implications are still awaited. © 2005 Lippincott Williams & Wilkins.
