4393. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 47007769
T1  - Metabolic and cardiovascular risk in the polycystic ovary syndrome
A1  - Cussons A.J.
A1  - Stuckey B.G.A.
A1  - Watts G.F. 
Y1  - 2005//
N2  - The polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is a common endocrine disorder in women that is associated with an increased prevalence of type 2 diabetes and other cardiovascular risk factors. It remains unclear, however, wh ether there is an associated increase in cardiovascular events in this condition. Increased prevalence of non-traditional risk factors, such as abnormalities of inflammation, coagulation, oxidative stress, arterial stiffness and endothelial dysfunction, has recently been reported in PCOS. Collectively, these studies have demonstrated biochemical, functional and structural abnormalities of the cardiovascular system. It seems that many of these cardiovascular abnormalities are related to the presence of insulin resistance and obesity rather than PCOS itself. Cohort studies of long-term cardiovascular outcome in PCOS and clinical trials of risk factor modification in women with this condition are required. Copyright © 2005 John Wiley & Sons, Ltd.
