4395. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 38028990
T1  - About 2 cases of menstrual disorders in association of bowel's parasitosis. A possible endocrine/paracrine parasites v/s host interaction
A1  - Giorlandino C.
A1  - Mangiafico L.
A1  - Barretta V.
A1  - Santoro L.
A1  - Mobili L.
A1  - Gaetano D.
A1  - Spano G.
A1  - Paolucci A.
A1  - Lena A. 
Y1  - 2003//
N2  - Introduction: We introduce two cases of patients, both coming from tropical countries and in therapy from many years with low dose of corticosteroids, because of symptoms of Arthritis, the first, and because of bronchial asthma, the second, committees to our observation in menstrual disorders, and spontaneously reverted after removed bowel's parasite. Material(s) and Method(s): In both patients, we carried out a complete anamnesis, hormonal and ultrasound screening to determine the case history. In both, the ovarian pattern failed to demonstrate the typical appearance of polycystic feature and the hormonal investigation showed a very singular profile: low values of gonadotropins and regular FSH/LH ratio with low values of Testosterone and DHT and quite normal values of Androstendione, high values of Estrone and quite normal values of Delta 5 Androgens. The Adrenal gland hormonal pattern ranged over the normal values. The Thyroid was also investigated without any significative result. In the second case, we investigated also 17-KS and urinary 19-Noretiocholanolone and 19-Norandrosterone that resulted high. In our patients, the situation resolved and the menstruations regularized after spontaneous lost of a long cestode (first case) and after correct therapy for bowel parasitosis (second case). Conclusion(s): Although the Literature shows that many examples of reciprocal endocrine interactions between parasites and hosts have been found in insects, arthropods and mammals, today nobody considers the possibility of reciprocal endocrine and/or paracrine interactions between parasites and hosts in differential diagnosis of menstrual disorders especially in women coming, or in contact, with tropical countries and in therapy with corticosteroids. Our centre, on the contrary, considers very important this reciprocal interactions for a correct diagnosis and therapy of some, otherwise unclassifiable, menstrual disorders.
