4424. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 39244018
ID  - 15625992 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15625992]
T1  - Benign adnexal masses in the adolescent
A1  - Powell J.K. 
Y1  - 2004//
N2  - Adnexal masses involving the ovaries or fallopian tubes are found frequently in adolescents. They may present with a variety of clinical symptoms, or may be found incidentally by pelvic exam or pelvic imaging. Management is dependent on the size, presumed etiology, risk of malignancy, likelihood of spontaneous regression, and severity of patient symptomatology. Many adnexal masses warrant expectant management or surveillance. If surgery is necessary, a laparoscopic approach can be taken in many patients, and conservative, fertility-sparing surgery should be encouraged. Surgeons and primary care providers should familiarize themselves with typical postoperative symptoms and be aware of the signs and symptoms of postoperative complications.
