4478. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 39287545
ID  - 15326421 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15326421]
T1  - Depression and insulin resistance: Applications to polycystic ovary syndrome
A1  - Brown A.J. 
Y1  - 2004//
N2  - Studies presented in this review raise interesting questions about the connections between depression and diabetes and offer insulin resistance as a potential common mediator of the 2 disorders. Epidemiologic studies argue that a diagnosis of depression predisposes to the subsequent development of diabetes. In individuals without diabetes, depression exacerbates insulin resistance, a key element of type 2 diabetes. And in these patients, treatment of depression results in a near-normalization of insulin sensitivity. Among individuals with diabetes, depression occurs about twice as often as in those without diabetes, and treatment of depression can improve glucose control, though this is not a consistent finding. If depression modulates insulin sensitivity, as suggested by the studies discussed in this review, then populations with underlying insulin resistance could demonstrate a more rapid deterioration in metabolic status from insulin resistance to type 2 diabetes in the setting of concomitant depression. This group includes women with PCOS and others with risk factors for type 2 diabetes. The rising prevalence of type 2 diabetes highlights the clinical importance of further evaluating strategies for preventing or slowing the progression from insulin resistance to hyperglycemia. Aggressive treatment of depression might be one of those strategies.
