4497. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 38680631
ID  - 15158520 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15158520]
T1  - The metabolic syndrome or the insulin resistance syndrome? Different names, different concepts, and different goals
A1  - Reaven G. 
Y1  - 2004//
N2  - The goal of this article has been to help clarify the difference between two terms, often used interchangeably, that refer to the clinical consequences that can arise from resistance to insulin-mediated glucose disposal and the homeostatic efforts to compensate for this fundamental defect. Perhaps the single point that deserves the most emphasis is that insulin resistance is not a disease but the description of a physiologic state that greatly increases the chances of an individual developing several closely related abnormalities and associated clinical syndromes. Insulin resistance does not necessarily result in the abnormalities and clinical syndromes listed in Boxes 2 and 3, and, to varying degrees, they can occur in the absence of insulin resistance. The primary value of the concept of an IRS is pedagogic; it provides the conceptual framework with which to place a substantial number of apparently unrelated biologic events into a pathophysiologic construct. Its primary goal is not to make a diagnosis but to increase understanding of why, for example, a woman with PCOS is more likely to develop type 2 diabetes than a woman with a normal menstrual history. This does not imply that the notion of an IRS is without clinical utility, and the apparent link between insulin resistance/compensatory hyperinsulinemia and the clinical course of breast cancer provides an obvious mechanistic target with which to evaluate new treatment options. The metabolic syndrome focuses on only one of the clinical syndromes associated with insulin resistance listed in Boxes 3, and its goal is explicitly to make a diagnosis to implement lifestyle changes with the goal of decreasing risk of CVD. Consequently, its value must be considered not in pathophysiologic terms but as a pragmatic approach to obtain a better clinical outcome. The fact that obesity is a variable that contributes to insulin resistance, not a consequence of the defect in insulin action, does not necessarily detract from the use of the metabolic syndrome. The possibility that the measure of obesity listed in Boxes 1 may be less than ideal or that the values for waist circumference may be most applicable to individuals of European ancestry, however, are issues that need further discussion. Similarly, what is the value of a diagnostic criterion of IFG when only approximately 5% of an apparently healthy population has that abnormality? The most fundamental question relates to the clinical use of making a diagnosis of the metabolic syndrome, however. Imagine two men who are identical in that neither met the ATP III waist circumference and fasting glucose criteria and both satisfied the blood pressure and triglyceride criteria, but they differed in that only one of them had an HDL-C concentration low enough to satisfy the third criteria necessary for a positive diagnosis of the metabolic syndrome. Are these individuals fundamentally different? Would the treatment options differ in any substantive way? The manner in which this question is answered determines how useful the concept of making a diagnosis of the metabolic syndrome proves to be.
