AN  - 37377777
ID  - 14607613 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14607613]
T1  - Ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome
A1  - Anonymous.
Y1  - 2003//
N2  - Experience with ovulation induction therapy and knowledge of OHSS pathophysiology, risk factors, and clinical features are key to preventing and managing OHSS. Mild manifestations of OHSS are fairly common, occurring in up to a third of exogenous gonadotropin-induced superovulation cycles. Worsening symptoms of OHSS can still usually be managed on an outpatient basis, but frequent monitoring and evaluation are essential. Serious illness resulting from OHSS is much less common, but it can be life-threatening. Hospitalization may be necessary for patients with serious illness resulting from OHSS.
