4566. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 36992809
T1  - Insulin resistance and Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome: From pathophysiology to patient care
A1  - Gonzalez M.R.R.
A1  - Vollenweider P.
A1  - Pralong F. 
Y1  - 2003//
N2  - Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS) is the most common endocrinopathy in women of reproductive age. Over the last two decades, the insulin resistance present in most affected patients has emerged as a central characteristic of the syndrome. This insulin resistance is probably playing an important physiopathological role not only in the dysmetabolic syndrome, but also in the hormonal abnormalities classically associated with PCOS. This review will focus upon the molecular mechanisms of the insulin resistance of PCOS, as well as on its clinical consequences: the hyper-androgenism and the ovulatory disorder. The etiopathogenic mechanisms involved are discussed in light of recent data regarding insulin signaling within the central nervous system.
