4575. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 36903295
T1  - Transcranial color coded Doppler evaluation of intracranial circulation in extracranial internal carotid artery occlusion
A1  - Subba Rao D.
A1  - Uma D.M.
A1  - Nagamani P.
A1  - Suvarna A.
A1  - Subhash K.
A1  - Subbalaxmi M.V. 
Y1  - 2003//
N2  - Objective: To assess the haemodynamics and collateral pathways of intracranial circulation in extracranial internal carotid artery (ICA) occlusion. Subjects and methods: Fifty patients in the age range of 16 to 72 years with extracranial ICA occlusion were included in the study done over a period of 2 years. Transcranial colour-coded Doppler sonography (TCCD) was performed on ATL HDI 3000 and GE Logic 500 units using dedicated TCCD probe through temporal and orbital windows. Attempt was made to visualise bilateral anterior cerebral (ACA), middle cerebral (MCA) and posterior cerebral (PCA) arteries, anterior and posterior communicating arteries (AcoA & PcoA) and ophthalmic artery (OA). The results were confirmed with computed tomographic angiography (CTA)/magnetic resonance angiography (MRA) in 30 patients. The collaterals were classified as ACoA, PCoA and ophthalmic artery. Result(s): Ipsilateral ICA was reformed in 90% of the patients. Predominant collateral pathways were contralateral ACA through AcoA (66%), ipsilateral PCA through PcoA and leptomeningeal collaterals (38%) and ophthalmic artery (30%). In about 22% of the patients, there was only one collateral pathway that was functional, 2 pathways in 64% and more than 2 in 14% of the patients. Altered flow dynamics were found with significant contralateral MCA or ICA disease. Conclusion(s): TCCD is an inexpensive, simple, non-invasive and sensitive modality in assessing the status of the intracranial circulation and collateral routes in extracranial ICA occlusion and is a valuable tool in deciding the management options.
