4618. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 32455509
ID  - 11376670 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11376670]
T1  - Infertility in American college alumnae
A1  - Wyshak G. 
Y1  - 2001//
N2  - Objective: The objective of this paper is to present data on prevalence of infertility, causes and treatments based on self-reports of a sample of American college alumnae. Method(s): A sample of 3940 American college alumnae, ages 37 to over 70 years, completed a self-administered questionnaire relating to infertility, its causes, treatment and treatment outcomes. Result(s): Of the entire sample (n=3940), 3.1% (n=121) had primary infertility; 14.0% (n=548) had secondary infertility and were treated; 4.7% (n=184) tried for more than 1 year without success but had pregnancies without treatment; and 62.4% had no problems with infertility; and 16% (n=616) did not try to get pregnant. The major causes were 'unexplained infertility' reported by 43.5%; low sperm count or low motility, 21.4%; and anovulatory cycles, 20.3%. Treatment by clomid was reported by 39.5%. The overall success rate, resulting from treatment was 45%. The highest success rate occurred when anovulatory cycles were treated with clomid. Conclusion(s): Prevalence of primary and secondary infertility in this sample of American women is approximately 17%, similar to that observed for Sub-Saharan Africa. © 2001 International Federation of Gynecology and Obstetrics.
