4672. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 35230073
T1  - Audit of FSH requesting can alter long-term practice
A1  - Lapworth R.
A1  - Anslow T.
A1  - Clawson T. 
Y1  - 2002//
N2  - A survey of requesting practice in 1994 confirmed that the majority of follicle stimulating hormone/lutenising hormone (FSH/LH) requests were for investigation of menopausal status and therefore inappropriate. In 1996, the introduction of guidelines for requesting FSH and LH reduced the percentage of tests in this patient group from 58% to less than 24% of the total. Inappropriate testing in menopausal women over 45 years decreased from 33.2% to approximately 10% of the total number of requests. This decrease in requesting in women over 45 years was sustained after closing the audit loop in 1998 but no further reductions in inappropriate testing were observed. Since 1994/95 requests for FSH/LH have decreased annually, which is in contrast to all other biochemistry tests. This suggests that requesting practice has been altered; initial recommendations having now become routine.
