4677. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 36118895
T1  - Individualizing treatment with atypical antipsychotics: Factors to consider in decision making
A1  - Nelson M. 
Y1  - 2002//
N2  - Use of atypical antipsychotic agents has risen as their clinical superiority has been demonstrated. However, their acquisition costs are higher than those for first-generation products. In an attempt to control costs, some antipsychotic treatment algorithms and guidelines have restricted access to some atypical antipsychotics. Antipsychotic guidelines should never be used as a prescribing mandate. Atypical antipsychotic agents should be equally available as first-line agents to account for both variabilities in these drugs and patient differences. The atypical antipsychotics have different pharmacologic, pharmacokinetic, and side-effect profiles. Their effects may also be influenced by patients' race, sex, and age. In addition, atypical antipsychotics may differ in their effects on subsets of schizophrenia symptoms, such as in managing agitation and aggression, controlling depression, reducing suicidal ideation, and improving cognition. Understanding these differences will lead to improved treatment of individual patients with schizophrenia.
