4718. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 34578216
T1  - Clinical uses of insulin-like growth factor binding protein-1 measurements
A1  - Livingstone C. 
Y1  - 2001//
N2  - Insulin-like growth factor binding protein-1 (IGFBP-1) is produced predominantly by liver and decidualised endometrium and found mainly in serum and amniotic fluid. It is negatively regulated by insulin at the level of transcription. The IGFBP-1 concentration in serum rises under conditions associated with low insulin levels viz fasting, poorly controlled insulin dependent diabetes mellitus and decreases under conditions of high insulin e.g. in the postprandial period and clinical conditions such as insulinomas and congenital hyperinsulinism. This relationship is lost in acute illness, possibly as a result of cytokine action. The principal emerging uses for IGFBP-1 measurements are in the assessment of insulin status, investigation of hypoglycaemia and assessment of cardiovascular risk. Here, the established and potential clinical uses of IGFBP-1 measurements are reviewed.
