4753. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 30331644
ID  - 10783435 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10783435]
T1  - Measuring quality in end-of-life care
A1  - Rosenfeld K.
A1  - Wenger N.S. 
Y1  - 2000//
N2  - This article has attempted to review conceptual models and measurement strategies for quality-of-care evaluation in patients who are near the end of life. Traditional quality-of-care models focusing on mortality and major morbidity do not capture the range of health outcomes that are important to patients nearing the end of life and their families. Although traditional models exclude dimensions such as self-determination, spiritual well-being, and family support, these are important to measure end-of-life care evaluations. Several of the process care measures, such as whether there was clinician-patient communication about goals of care or whether a symptom assessment occurred, can be applied to the full range of geriatric patients. Even though formal quality-of-care evaluation is usually left to researchers and quality management personnel, clinicians can use the models and measurement tools discussed in this article to optimize their care for dying patients. Even busy clinicians could regularly use a single-item QOL measure ('How would you rate your overall quality of life?') and a 0-to-10 rating scale of important symptoms. Furthermore, clinical practices could institute routine collection of information on patients' end-of-life care goals and treatment preferences. Regularly recording these items not only can permit clinicians to make therapeutic interventions, but it also allows clinicians to monitor their patients' progress over time and to characterize the performance of their practice in delivering quality care to dying patients. Several of the measurement techniques and survey items to carry out quality- of-care assessment have been assembled by Teno in the 'Toolkit' that can be accessed on the Internet at http://www.chcr.brown.edu/pcoc/tool.htm. These tools and others presented in this summary should permit end-of-life process assessment to be added to other quality-of-care evaluations conducted on geriatric patients. More intensive evaluation of end-of-life care among geriatric patients can be carried out by selecting appropriate patient samples as noted in the last section of this article. These can explore the full range of domains presented in Table 1. More research is needed to identify improved techniques to identify patient samples for evaluation of end-of-life care and measurement tools to carry out such assessment. This research will provide the data needed to improve end-of-life care for geriatric patients.
