4792. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 26388928
ID  - 8956942 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8956942]
T1  - Long-term transcutaneons monitoring of oxygen tension and carbon dioxide at 42degreeC in critically ill neonates: Improved performance of the tcpo2 monitor with topical metabolic inhibition
A1  - Fanconi S.
A1  - Tschupp A.
A1  - Molinari L. 
Y1  - 1996//
N2  - Whereas during the last few years handling of the transcutaneous PO2 (tcPO2) and PCO2 (tcPCO2) sensor has been simplified, the high electrode temperature and the short application time remain major drawbacks. In order to determine whether the application of a topical metabolic inhibitor allows reliable measurement at a sensor temperature of 42degreeC for a period of up to 12 h, we performed a prospective, open, nonrandomized study in a sequential sample of 20 critically ill neonates. A total of 120 comparisons (six repeated measurements per patient) between arterial and transcutaneous values were obtained. Transcutaneous values were measured with a control sensor at 44degreeC (conventional contact medium, average application time 3 h) and a test sensor at 42degreeC (Eugenol solution, average application time 8 h). Comparison of tcPO2 and PaO2 at 42degreeC (Eugenol solution) showed a mean difference of +0.16 kPa (range +1.60 to -2.00 kPa), limits of agreement +1.88 and -1.56 kPa. Comparison of tcPO2 and PaO2 at 44degreeC (control sensor) revealed a mean difference of +0.02 kPa (range +2.60 to -1.90 kPa), limits of agreement +2.12 and -2.08 kPa. Comparison of tcPCO2 and PaCO2 at 42degree C (Eugenol solution) showed a mean difference of +0.91 (range +2.30 to +0.10 kPa), limits of agreement +2.24 and -0.42 kPa. Comparison of tcPCO2 and PaCOat 44degreeC (control sensor) revealed a mean difference of +0.63 kPa (range 1.50 to -0.30 kPa), limits of agreement +1.73 and -0.47 kPa. Conclusion. Our results show that the use of an Eugenol solution allows reliable measurement of tcPO2 at a heating temperature of 42degreeC; the application time can be prolongued up to a maximum of 12 h without aggravating the skin lesions. The performance of the tcPCO2 monitor was slightly worse at 42degreeC than at 44degreeC suggesting that for the Eugenol solution the metabolic offset should be corrected.
