AN  - 29379357
ID  - 10446813 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10446813]
T1  - Sublingual capnometry: A new noninvasive measurement for diagnosis and quantitation of severity of circulatory shock
A1  - Weil M.H.
A1  - Nakagawa Y.
A1  - Tang W.
A1  - Sato Y.
A1  - Ercoli F.
A1  - Finegan R.
A1  - Grayman G.
A1  - Bisera J. 
Y1  - 1999//
N2  - Objective: To investigate the feasibility and predictive value of sublingual PCO2 (PSLCO2) measurements as a noninvasive and early indicator of systemic perfusion failure. Design(s): A prospective, criterion study. Setting(s): Emergency department and medical and surgical intensive care units of an urban community medical center. Participants and Patients: Five normal human volunteers and 46 patients with acutely life-threatening illness or injuries. Intervention(s): Intra-arterial or automated cuff blood pressure and arterial blood lactate (LAC) were measured concurrently with PSLCO2. Result(s): PSLCO2 in five healthy volunteers was 45.2 +/- 0.7 mm Hg (mean +/- SD). Twenty-six patients with physical signs of circulatory shock and LAC > 2.5 mmol/L had a PSLCO2 of 81 +/- 24 mm Hg. This contrasted with patients admitted without clinical signs of shock and LAC of < 2.5 mmol/L who had a PSLCO2 of 53 +/- 8 mm Hg (p < .001). The initial PSLCO2 of 12 patients who died before recovery from shock was 93 +/- 27 mm Hg, and this contrasted with 58 +/- 11 mm Hg (p < .001) in hospital survivors. Increases in PSLCO2 were correlated with increases in LAC (r2 = .84; p < .001). When PSLCO2 exceeded a threshold of 70 mm Hg, its positive predictive value for the presence of physical signs of circulatory shock was 1.00. When it was < 70 mm Hg, it predicted survival with a predictive value of 0.93. Conclusion(s): PSLCO2 may serve as a technically simple and noninvasive clinical measurement for the diagnosis and estimation of the severity of circulatory shock states.
