T1  - Augmented hypoxic ventilatory response in men at altitude
A1  - Sato M.
A1  - Severinghaus J.W.
A1  - Powell F.L.
A1  - Xu F.-D.
A1  - Spellman Jr. M.J. 
Y1  - 1992//
N2  - To test the hypothesis that the hypoxic ventilatory response (HVR) of an individual is a constant unaffected by acclimatization, isocapnic 5-min step HVR, as DELTAVI/DELTASa(O2) (l . min-1 . %-1, where VI is inspired ventilation and Sa(O2) is arterial O2 saturation), was tested in six normal males at sea level (SL), after 1-5 days at 3,810-m altitude (AL1-3), and three times over 1 wk after altitude exposure (PAL1-3). Equal medullary central ventilatory drive was sought at both altitudes by testing HVR after > 15 min of hyperoxia to eliminate possible ambient hypoxic ventilatory depression (HVD), choosing for isocapnia a P'CO2 (end tidal) elevated sufficiently to drive hyperoxic VI to 140 ml . kg-1 . min-1. Mean P'CO2 was 45.4 +/- 1.7 Torr at SL and 33.3 +/- 1.8 Torr on AL3, compared with the respective resting control end-tidal PCO2 of 42.3 +/- 2.0 and 30.8 +/- 2.6 Torr. SL HVR of 0.91 +/- 0.38 was unchanged on AL1 (30 +/- 18 h) at 1.04 +/- 0.37 but rose (P < 0.05) to 1.27 +/- 0.57 on AL2 (3.2 +/- 0.8 days) and 1.46 +/- 0.59 on AL3 (4.8 +/- 0.4 days) and remained high on PAL1 at 1.44 +/- 0.54 and PAL2 at 1.37 +/- 0.78 but not on PAL3 (days 4-7). HVR was independent of test Sa(O2) (range 60-90%). Hyperoxic HCVR (CO2 response) was increased on AL3 and PAL1. Arterial pH at 65% Sa(O2) was 7.378 +/- 0.019 at SL, 7.44 +/- 0.018 on AL2, and 7.412 +/- 0.023 on AL3. We confirm previous evidence that peripheral chemosensitivity as measured by HVR increases with time at altitude. At both altitudes, during 25 min of isocapnic hypoxia (77% Sa(O2)), ventilation declined 45-63% from its peak at 2.5-5 min, demonstrating HVD. However, at 25 min, a further Sa(O2) decrease from 77 to 65% increased ventilation as if HVD were not present. The differential HVR slope was 133 +/- 68% of the undepressed control (P < 0.02). This suggests that HVD may not be a depression of integrating centers but, rather, a resetting of the VI-pH relationship of central chemoreceptors, perhaps related to the lactic acid generated by these medullary ventral cells in hypoxia.
