5050. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase <1980 to 1987>
AN  - 14018666
ID  - 6491546 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=6491546]
T1  - Ovulation control: The right number or nothing
A1  - Akin E.
A1  - Lacker H.M. 
Y1  - 1984//
N2  - The number of follicles which mature from cycle to cycle-the ovulation number-is remarkably constant, as reflected in the narrow range of litter sizes within a species. It is easy to imagine an ovulation number of one. The first mature follicle need only transmit a signal to the other developing follicles causing them to degenerate. The analogy here would be with the fertilization reaction which prevents polyspermy. However, regulation for other numbers occurs and we want to clarify how this can happen. Occasionally, the cycle is broken and the system enters a pathological equilibrium called anovulation, characterized by the absence of ovulation and by an intermediate level of estradiol in the circulation. We examine how this anovulatory behavior may occur. This is important because in response to a constant estradiol level the uterine lining grows continuously and may eventually assume a cancer-like state. A final question concerns the regulation of timing. The process of follicle activation is apparently random. Furthermore, the growing follicles regress at different times and stages of maturity yet the entire process is so organized that periodic cycles occur. In order to answer the questions Lacker and Lacker and Peskin developed a differential equations model for the maturation process. Our purpose here is to generalize their model so that the qualitative results can be understood by looking at the graph of two functions. We also relate our results to their - stochastic - model of follicle activation.
